40|$|The {{properties}} of the <b>cosmic</b> microwave <b>background</b> <b>radiation</b> provide unique constraints on cosmological models, i. e. on the content, history, and evolution of the Universe. I discuss the latest measurements of the spectral and spatial {{properties of}} the <b>cosmic</b> microwave <b>background</b> <b>radiation.</b> Recent measurements from NASA's <b>Cosmic</b> <b>Background</b> Explorer (COBE) satellite, and from balloon-borne and ground-based platforms, are summarized and their cosmological implications are discussed. Comment: 10 pages of uuencoded postscript To Appear in Nuclear Physics B Proceedings Supplements ("Neutrino 94 ", Eilat, Israel, June 1994...|$|R
